g":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":true},"margin_mobile":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"10","left":"0","isLinked":false}},"elements":[{"id":"55b0e540","settings":{"editor":"<p>&gt; THE OXFORD WAY<\/p>","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_family":"Roboto","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":36,"sizes":[]},"typography_font_weight":"600","typography_text_transform":"uppercase","typography_line_height":{"unit":"px","size":5,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height_tablet":{"unit":"em","size":1.2,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height_mobile":{"unit":"px","size":"","sizes":[]},"_padding":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":false},"_css_classes":"top_breadcrum_2026","pa_condition_repeater":[{"_id":"38fd671"}],"__globals__":{"text_color":"globals\/colors?id=64e95d4"},"_padding_mobile":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":true}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"},{"id":"ea2db64","settings":{"title":"Institutional Consulting: Expanding Access, Enhancing Outcomes","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":68,"sizes":[]},"typography_font_weight":"400","pa_condition_repeater":[{"_id":"2f29de9"}],"_background_image":{"url":"","id":"","alt":"","source":"library"},"__globals__":{"title_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"},"align":"left","_background_position":"center left","_background_repeat":"no-repeat","header_size":"h1","_padding":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"20","left":"0","isLinked":false},"align_mobile":"left","_margin_mobile":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":true},"_element_id":"heading_2026","typography_line_height":{"unit":"em","size":1.2,"sizes":[]},"typography_line_height_tablet_extra":{"unit":"em","size":"","sizes":[]}},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"heading","elType":"widget"}],"isInner":true,"elType":"column"},{"id":"4ab15351","settings":{"_column_size":50,"_inline_size":null,"_element_id":"scroll_col","css_classes":"scrollbar-inner ceo_p","pa_condition_repeater":[{"_id":"185868e"}],"padding_tablet":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":false}},"elements":[{"id":"446af711","settings":{"editor":"<p>At Oxford, we believe institutional clients deserve a level of sophistication comparable to that of the largest endowments and pension funds, without sacrificing practicality or flexibility. That conviction shapes the way we approach consulting for boards, committees and business owners navigating complex retirement or reserve obligations.<\/p><p>Our work often begins with mid-sized endowments and foundations looking to move beyond traditional stocks and bonds. By incorporating private equity, direct investments and absolute-return strategies, we can design portfolios that seek higher return potential with reduced sensitivity to inflation and interest rates. This reflects strategies used by larger foundations but in a format designed for clients in the $25 to $500 million range.<\/p><p>Another growing area is employee stock ownership plans (ESOPs). These structures give business owners liquidity while rewarding employees with long-term participation in their companies. On the consulting side, we help organizations plan ahead by building reserves to meet future participant obligations much in the same way pension plans do. Because we understand both the ownership and institutional perspectives, we offer insight into managing these assets prudently while supporting the company\u2019s broader mission.<\/p><p>Institutional clients are sharply focused on meeting distribution requirements, typically 4.5% to 5% annually, while also covering expenses and inflation. With inflation above 3%, an 8% return is needed just to maintain principal. Public equities have delivered strong results in recent years, but we view private equity and other diversifying strategies as important components for sustaining long-term obligations. For pension plans, rising rates have improved liability calculations. Even so, disciplined investment strategies remain essential to keep funding ratios strong and contribution requirements manageable.<\/p><p>The environment remains uncertain. Fiscal policy shifts, trade disputes and evolving Federal Reserve decisions all shape the landscape for institutional investors. Our answer continues to be broad diversification: owning a wide range of assets built to perform under different conditions. That discipline supported client objectives in 2025 and remains central to our work in 2026.<\/p><p>Ultimately, institutional consulting is about stewardship. Whether guiding committees on participant-directed plans, helping a business through an ESOP transition or designing endowment strategies that last generations, our role is to provide clarity, sophistication and stability in a noisy world. By giving clients access to the same caliber of opportunities as the largest institutions and tailoring them to their specific needs, we help them fulfill their missions with confidence.<\/p>","typography_typography":"custom","typography_font_family":"Roboto","typography_font_size":{"unit":"px","size":36,"sizes":[]},"typography_font_weight":"400","__globals__":{"text_color":"globals\/colors?id=64e95d4","_background_color":""},"text_shadow_text_shadow":{"horizontal":0,"vertical":0,"blur":12,"color":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)"},"pa_condition_repeater":[{"_id":"cc26f2d"}],"text_color":"#000000","_background_background":"classic","align_mobile":"left"},"elements":[],"isInner":false,"widgetType":"text-editor","elType":"widget"}],"isInner":true,"elType":"column"}],"isInner":true,"elType":"section"}],"isInner":false,"elType":"column"}],"isInner":false,"elType":"section"}],"page_settings":[],"version":"0.4","title":"The Oxford Way &#8211; Institutional Consulting &#8211; Page Template","type":"section"}